- Chlorine substituent: This will increase the melting point due to the molecular mass and the polarity it introduces; Estimated effect: +30°C. 
- Phenyl group: It provides additional pi-pi stacking opportunities, which increases the melting point; Estimated effect: +20°C per phenyl group (total for two: +40°C). 
- Alkyne group: This may slightly raise the melting point due to the linearity and potential for dipole interactions; Estimated effect: +10°C. 
- Triazole group: The presence of nitrogen and the potential for hydrogen bonding will considerably increase the melting point; Estimated effect: +50°C. 
- Alkyl chains (propyl and tert-butyl): These generally increase the melting point because of increased van der Waals forces due to larger molecular surface area; Estimated effect: +5°C each (total: +10°C). 
Therefore, considering all the increments, the prediction for the melting point of fenbuconazole can be made.
Prediction: Summing up all the estimated effects: 5.5 (benzene) + 30 (chlorine) + 40 (two phenyl groups) + 10 (alkyne) + 50 (triazole) + 10 (alkyl chains) = 145.5°C
